                        <interp inst="t18290409-280-victim2548" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                     
                   and another, his masters
            </rs>; and 
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-280-defend2550" type="defendantName">
                     EDWARD 
                     PAYSON
                  <interp inst="t18290409-280-defend2550" type="surname" value="PAYSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-defend2550" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-defend2550" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18290409-280-off1580" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-off1580" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-off1580" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>
               feloniously receiving the same, he well knowing them to have been stolen
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-280-person2551">
                  JOHN 
                  MANSFIELD
               <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2551" type="surname" value="MANSFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2551" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2551" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I manage the business of the prosecutors, who are <rs id="t18290409-280-viclabel1581" type="occupation">earthenware manufacturer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-victim2548 t18290409-280-viclabel1581"></join>s, and live in <placeName id="t18290409-280-crimeloc1582">Barbican</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-280-crimeloc1582" type="placeName" value="Barbican"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-280-crimeloc1582" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-off1578 t18290409-280-crimeloc1582"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-off1580 t18290409-280-crimeloc1582"></join>. Hillman was in their employ for three or four years, as a kind of <rs id="t18290409-280-deflabel1583" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-defend2546 t18290409-280-deflabel1583"></join> - I was going along Smithfield on the 26th of March, and overtook Hargrave with a basket of goods on his head; he did not give me any information, but I sent a person to Payson's with my young man, who is not here; he brought a pattern of some goods; I went to Payson's lodging on the 2d of April, in <placeName id="t18290409-280-crimeloc1584">Three Tun-court, Redcross-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-280-crimeloc1584" type="placeName" value="Three Tun-court, Redcross-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-280-crimeloc1584" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-off1578 t18290409-280-crimeloc1584"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-280-off1580 t18290409-280-crimeloc1584"></join>, and found him there - I told him I had accused my young man, Hillman, of robbing me, and he had confessed it, and said that Payson had received the goods and paid 6d. per dozen for them; he said he had not, but that he had received the goods for gown pieces, which Hillman had had of him, and he had given him some money besides; the price of the goods were two-thirds less than they could be purchased for on his own account - I saw the two prisoners afterwards together; Payson asked Hillman whether what I had said was true - Hillman said it was, about his paying 6d. a dozen for them; Payson denied having paid any money for them, except two or three shillings - there was property found in both their lodgings, cups, saucers, and a great many other things; the greater part was found in Payson's lodgings.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. What did you find at Hillman's? A. The officer has it; I had a communication with Hillman before I saw Payson, but not before I sent to him - I did tell Hillman that if he would confess the extent to which he had been robbing us, I would not prosecute him; and he said, what Hargrave had was all he had robbed us of.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-280-person2552">
                  GEORGE 
                  HARGRAVE
               <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2552" type="surname" value="HARGRAVE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2552" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2552" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I deal in earthenware, and live in Sandy-street, Bishopsgate. I have seen the prisoners, but not in company - I dealt with Payson once only, which was on the 26th of March; I bought twelve dozen of plates, five dozen of egg-cups, and four dozen and half of salts; I paid 1s. 3d. a dozen for the plates - it was no very great bargain - I could buy them at Mr. Mansfield's for 1s. 4d.; I have the articles now at home - I have sold about a dozen egg-cups; Mr. Mansfield saw me going along, and told me they were his; Payson told me he had bought them at Mr. Bullen's sale.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by MR. RYLAND. Q. Where does Mr. Mansfield live? A. In Barbican; I bought them between eleven and twelve o'clock, and he met me about one - I had seen Payson the day before in Petticoat-lane, where I stand every afternoon to sell goods; he asked me if I would buy some blue muffin-plates, and told me he lived at No. 3, Three Tun-court, Redcross-street - I offered him a 5l. note; there was some difficulty about changing it, and I went to Mr. Mansfield for change as I deal there - I told him I should go there; he made no objection - I returned in about two hours, and he was still there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-280-person2553">
                  JOSEPH 
                  ORTON
               <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2553" type="surname" value="ORTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2553" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2553" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I was sent for to<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090124"></xptr>Mr. Mansfield, and took Payson to the computer - I found on him 1l. 0s. 9d., and the key of his door; I went to his lodgings, and found the greater part of this property concealed under a bedstead, which goes back with folding doors, from the top to the bottom - here are three pairs of images, three china jugs, one blue mug, twelve blue papboats, four busts, one blue butter-pan, seventy-two eggcups, twenty-one blue basons, and a great variety of other things which Mr. Mansfield identified; Payson said he would bring witnesses to prove that he bought part of it of Mr. Mansfield - the next morning I asked him if he could bring those witnesses; he said,</p>
               <p>"I never told you so" - I went with Howard to take Hillman, and on him was found a key which opens Payson's door.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. RYLAND. Q. Did Payson tell you where he lodged? A. Yes; I did not know him before - it is a small room; the things were mostly under a bedstead - there were a number of basons in a closet, some earthenware in other parts of the room, and images on the mantel-piece; the other articles were on a sofa under a coat.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-280-person2554">
                  ROBERT 
                  HOWARD
               <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2554" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2554" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-person2554" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I went to Mr. Mansfield's and then to Hillman's lodging, where I got twelve coffee cups, five cruets, and one china dog - I found this key on him, which opens Payson's lodging.</p>
               <p>The prosecutors not being able to identify the property, the prisoners were <rs id="t18290409-280-verdict1585" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-280-verdict1585" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               ACQUITTED
            </rs>.</p>
